{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2015}} {{Infobox album | name = Hard Core | type = mixtape | artist = [[Lil' Kim]] | cover = Hard Core mixtape cover.jpg | alt = | released = {{start date|2014|9|11}} | recorded = | venue = | studio = | genre = [[Hard Core Hip hop music|Hip hop]] | length = {{duration|m=34|s=43}} | label = [[International Rock Star Records|I.R.S Records]] | producer = | prev_title = [[Black Friday (Lil' Kim mixtape)|Black Friday]] | prev_year = 2011 | next_title = [[Lil Kim Season]] | next_year = 2016 | misc = {{Singles | name = Hard Core 2K14 | type = Mixtape | single1 = Dead Gal Walking | single1date = October 31, 2013 | single2 = I Am Kimmy Blanco | single2date = November 30, 2013 | single3 = Haterz | single3date = April 24, 2014 | single4 = Identity Theft | single4date = August 6, 2014 }} }}
'''''Hard Core''''' (also known as '''''Hard Core 2K14''''') is the third [[Mixtape#Mixtapes in hip hop|mixtape]] by American recording artist [[Lil' Kim]], released on September 11, 2014 by [[International Rock Star Records|I.R.S Records]]. The mixtape was first announced on July 26, 2013, and originally had a release date of October 31, 2013, but was pushed back due to Jones' [[pregnancy]].
== Background == With fans often suggesting that Kim create something ''[[Hard Core (Lil' Kim album)|Hard Core]]'' inspired, the idea to recreate the "movement" came from Kim's manager, Big Fendi.<ref name="stacks">{{cite web|author=Ms. Bels|title=[EXCLUSIVE] Cocaine Raps & Mindstates: Lil Kim Speaks on 'Hard Core 2K14'|url=http://www.stacksmag.net/2014/09/exclusive-cocaine-raps-mindstates-lil-kim-speaks-hard-core-2k14.html|work=Stacks Magazine|date=September 15, 2014 |accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> News of the project first began circulating on July 10, 2013 when Big Mike The Ruler, who hosted Kim's previous mixtape, ''[[Black Friday (Lil' Kim mixtape)|Black Friday]]'', tweeted that work was beginning on a new mixtape and for [[Instrumental|beats]] to be sent in<ref>{{cite web|last=Khloe|first=Jasmine|title=Lil' Kim to release another Mixtape? Details Inside.|url=http://thewomenofhiphop.com/2013/07/10/lil-kim-to-release-another-mixtape-details-inside/|work=Woman of Hip Hop|date=July 10, 2013|accessdate=September 28, 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026175639/http://thewomenofhiphop.com/2013/07/10/lil-kim-to-release-another-mixtape-details-inside/|archivedate=October 26, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kim officially announced the mixtape, ''Hard Core 2K13'', on July 26, 2013, along with the cover art.<ref name="hnhh">{{cite web|last=Lilah|first=Rose|title=Lil Kim Announces New Mixtape "Hard Core: Back 2 Da Streetz" [Update: Project Delayed]|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/lil-kim-announces-new-mixtape-hard-core-back-2-da-streetz-news.6583.html|work=Hot New Hip Hop|date=October 31, 2013|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> On September 11, 2013, Kim announced that the mixtape would be released on October 31, 2013.<ref name="hnhh" /> On the day of release it was announced by Kim's manager, Big Fendi, that the mixtape had been pushed back to November 29, 2013, due to work not being completed on an [[Mobile app|app]] that was to accompany the mixtape.<ref name="hnhh" /> That same day, the track list was released.<ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Trevor|title=Lil Kim Reveals Tracklist & Features For "Hard Core 2K13" Mixtape|url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/lil-kim-reveals-news.8370.html|work=Hot New Hip Hop|date=December 1, 2013 |accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> The mixtape was eventually pushed back again due to Kim's pregnancy and a new release date wasn't given until August 8, 2014 when it was announced that ''Hard Core 2K14'' would be released on September 11, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=LIL' KIM ANNOUNCES 'HARD CORE' MIXTAPE RELEASE DATE|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/08/08/lil-kim-announces-hard-core-mixtape-release-date/|work=Rap-Up|date=August 8, 2014 |accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> Kim choose to release the mixtape on September 11 as a way of remembering those who died in the [[September 11 attacks]] in 2001 and as a way of making those affected by the tragedy smile.<ref name="bossip">{{cite web|last=|first=|title=BOSSIP Exclusive: Lil Kim Talks Baby Royal Reign, Diddy And Her Freaky-Deeky Lyric Filled 'Hard Core' Mixtape 'It's Always Sexual With Me'|url=http://bossip.com/1030354/bossip-exclusive-lil-kim-talks-baby-royal-reign-diddy-and-her-freaky-deeky-lyric-filled-hard-core-mixtape-its-always-sexual-with-me/|work=Bossip |date=September 11, 2014 |accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> A new cover was revealed on September 9, 2014, alluding to her debut album ''[[Hard Core (Lil' Kim album)|Hard Core]]'' from 1996. The cover also pays homage to [[LL Cool J]]'s 1989 album ''[[Walking with a Panther]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=LIL' KIM UNVEILS 'HARD CORE' MIXTAPE COVER|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/09/09/lil-kim-unveils-hard-core-mixtape-cover/|work=Rap-Up|date=September 9, 2014 |accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>
== Music and lyrics == Although they share the same name, ''Hard Core 2K14'' was never intended to serve as a part two to her debut album, ''[[Hard Core (Lil' Kim album)|Hard Core]]''. Kim only wanted to give listeners a "taste" of the original.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sanders|first=Shamika|title=Lil' Kim Talks Biggie Writing Her Rhymes & Says She Still Feels His Spirit In The Studio [EXCLUSIVE]|url=http://hellobeautiful.com/2014/09/23/lil-kim-talks-biggie-new-mixtape-exclusive/|work=Hello Beautiful|date=September 23, 2014 |accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> The title was more to do with recapturing the feeling that you got when you listened to her debut, a feeling Kim called "cocaine raps".<ref name="stacks" /> Kim felt that the lyrical content also had a common feel with that of her debut,<ref name="stacks" /> describing it as "heavy" and "sexual".<ref name="bossip" />
== Promotion == On September 20, 2014, Kim performed at [[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]'s first annual ''SOURCE360'' concert at [[Barclays Center]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Horowitz|first=Steven J|title=Wu-Tang Clan & Lil' Kim Reign in Brooklyn: Live Review|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/6259175/wu-tang-clan-lil-kim-reign-in-brooklyn-live-review|work=Billboard|date=September 20, 2014 |accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref>
== Critical reception == ''Hard Core'' received negative reviews from critics. A writer for ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' wrote "With the original [[Hard Core (Lil' Kim album)|Hard Core]] ranking with the best in the mafioso genre, ''Hard Core 2k14'' plays more of a reminder of who Lil Kim once was."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/reviews/2014/09/lil-kim-hardcore-2k14-mixtape-review/|title=Lil Kim Can't Recapture Her Glory Days On 'Hard Core 2k14' Mixtape|work=XXL|accessdate=May 31, 2015}}</ref>
